.TH "SOVEREIGN-OSCTL-OPERATIONS" "1" "2026-07-14" "sovereign-os 0.3.0" "sovereign-os Operator Manual"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
sovereign-osctl-operations - operations, observability, and recovery
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] \f[I]command\f[R] [\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
System status, diagnostics, maintenance, metrics, alerts, journals,
histories, snapshots, notifications, dashboards, and daily operator
workflows.
.PP
This page owns 39 top-level commands.
Ownership is defined in
\f[V]docs/man/sovereign-osctl-command-topics.json\f[R] and checked
against the real dispatcher.
The synopsis and descriptions are grounded in the command handler or
delegated-script contract at this build revision.
The top-level help is a discovery summary, not an exhaustive grammar.
.SH SAFETY MODEL
.PP
Most inspection verbs are read-only.
Maintenance, snapshot, restore, notification, service, and remediation
verbs may require root or explicit apply gates.
Preserve command output when escalating an incident.
.PP
Read-only discovery should precede mutation.
JSON output, when offered, is the stable surface for automation; human
output is intended for direct operator use.
.SH COMMON WORKFLOW
.IP "1." 3
Confirm the installed revision with \f[B]sovereign-osctl version\f[R].
.IP "2." 3
Inspect the relevant \f[B]status\f[R], \f[B]show\f[R], \f[B]list\f[R],
\f[B]info\f[R], \f[B]plan\f[R], or \f[B]doctor\f[R] surface.
.IP "3." 3
Save machine-readable output when \f[V]--json\f[R] is available.
.IP "4." 3
Review profile, device, backend, policy, and target selection.
.IP "5." 3
Apply the smallest scoped mutation, then re-run health/status.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sovereign-osctl status --json
sovereign-osctl doctor
sovereign-osctl alerts --json
sovereign-osctl journal errors
sovereign-osctl maintenance list
sovereign-osctl commands --json
sovereign-osctl help thermals
sovereign-osctl completion zsh > \[ti]/.zfunc/_sovereign-osctl
\f[R]
.fi
